{
  "texts": [
    "MetaCost, as introduced by Domingos (1999), can be conceptually dissected into three phases: Private ensemble building, relabelling, and classification (Siers and Islam 2020).",
    "MetaCost starts by creating multiple bootstrap samples from the initial training set following the bagging ensemble method, and each of these samples is used to train individual classifiers.",
    "These classifiers are then aggregated, either through averaging if the classifier used produces class probabilities or through a majority-voting scheme, to determine the probabilities of each example belonging to different classes.",
    "The original training examples in the dataset are subsequently relabelled to minimise the conditional risk defined in Equation 2.",
    "The resulting relabelled training data are then utilised to train the final classifier."
  ]
}